com.i2group.apollo.model.schema.transport

Class GeospatialPropertyValue

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.i2group.apollo.model.schema.transport.PropertyValue
      • com.i2group.apollo.model.schema.transport.ComplexPropertyValue
        • com.i2group.apollo.model.schema.transport.GeospatialPropertyValue

  • public final class GeospatialPropertyValue
extends ComplexPropertyValue
    A ComplexPropertyValue that represents a geospatial location.

    The value consists of two, four, or more CompoundPropertyValues, depending on what information it contains. The first two CompoundPropertyValues are mandatory.

    The first CompoundPropertyValue contains the WGS84 latitude and longitude of the geospatial location, where the order is important:

    1. A string representing the latitude in degrees, which must be in the range -90 to 90
    2. A string representing the longitude in degrees, which must be in the range -180 to 180
    The second CompoundPropertyValue contains a machine-readable form of the geospatial location. This information includes a latitude and longitude, plus information about the spatial reference system in which the latitude and longitude are to be interpreted:
    1. A string representing the latitude, in units appropriate for the spatial reference system
    2. A string representing the longitude, in units appropriate for the spatial reference system
    3. A string containing the name of the issuing authority of the spatial reference system
    4. A string containing the identifier (SRID) of the spatial reference system
    Any additional entries in the GeospatialPropertyValue contain source data: the geospatial information before it was converted to machine-readable form. When present, the third CompoundPropertyValue must contain a single string that describes the type of the source data, and there must be at least one more CompoundPropertyValue containing the source data itself. By definition, the structure of the fourth and any further entries is not prescribed.
    Since:
    4.0
